{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646239"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:27:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:27:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18164"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18164"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10878"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79293"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10878"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18164"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64615"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7163"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25302"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25305"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79293"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a primary function of the back?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Produces red blood cells","Facilitates locomotion","Filters blood","Synthesises vitamin D","Regulates body temperature"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of the back is to \u003Cstrong\u003Efacilitate locomotion\u003C/strong\u003E. The back, particularly the spine, provides structural support and stability, allowing for movement and flexibility. It plays a crucial role in maintaining posture and enabling activities such as walking, running, and bending.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProducing red blood cells\u003C/strong\u003E is a function of the bone marrow, not the back itself. While the vertebrae contain bone marrow, the back\u0027s primary role is not haematopoiesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegulating body temperature\u003C/strong\u003E is a function of the hypothalamus and the skin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynthesising vitamin D\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in the skin upon exposure to sunlight.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFiltering blood\u003C/strong\u003E is a function of the kidneys.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The back plays a crucial role in facilitating locomotion by providing support and stability to the body.","The back is involved in maintaining posture and allowing for a range of movements.","The back protects the spinal cord and supports the weight of the upper body."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","DeSai C, Reddy V, Agarwal A. Anatomy, Back, Vertebral Column. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525969/"]},"relati